\section{One key namespace, two binding tiers}{

There is no separate "VSI option" key type - \code{AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID} and \code{GDAL_HTTP_TIMEOUT} live in
the same namespace. What differs is the tier a \emph{value} is bound at. GDAL resolves an option for
a path by checking the path-specific store first (\code{VSISetPathSpecificOption()}; longest-matching
prefix wins), then falling through the ordinary chain: thread-local, global in-memory
(\code{CPLSetConfigOption()}, which also holds config-file values loaded at GDAL initialization),
environment variable (live \code{getenv()}), built-in default. A \code{\link[=gdal_vsi_opts]{gdal_vsi_opts()}} \emph{without} a
\code{vsi_path} is therefore just config opts and merges into the global channel; \emph{with} a
\code{vsi_path} it is kept path-bound in the \code{vsi} channel.
}

\section{Rendering}{

\code{as_gdal_args()} renders the global channel as \verb{--config KEY=VALUE} CLI tokens. Path-bound VSI
options \strong{cannot} be expressed on the CLI at all - GDAL only accepts them in-process
(\code{\link[gdalraster:vsi_set_path_option]{gdalraster::vsi_set_path_option()}}) or via the config file \verb{[credentials]} section - so they
are omitted with a message by default; \code{flatten_vsi = TRUE} emits them as global \code{--config}
tokens instead (loses the path scoping; warns when paths carry conflicting values for the same
key). \code{\link[=gdal_config_file_write]{gdal_config_file_write()}} is the only lossless serialization of a full \code{gdal_config}.
}

